2. Custom Exceptions (Program-Specific Errors) ‚ö†Ô∏è
üß† Logic:While Java provides many built-in exceptions (like IOException, NullPointerException), it is often necessary to define $\mathbf{Custom~Exceptions}$ (User-Defined Exceptions) to handle specific business logic errors within an application.To create a custom exception, you must extend one of the existing exception classes:Extend $\mathbf{`Exception`}$: Creates a Checked Exception (must be handled/declared). Use this for recoverable errors.Extend $\mathbf{`RuntimeException`}$: Creates an Unchecked Exception (handling is optional). Use this for programming bugs or non-recoverable errors.üìå Example:Java// Custom Checked Exception (Must be handled by caller)
class InsufficientFundsException extends Exception {
    public InsufficientFundsException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}

// Method that throws the custom exception
public void withdraw(int amount) throws InsufficientFundsException {
    if (amount > balance) {
        throw new InsufficientFundsException("Account balance is too low.");
    }
    // continue withdrawal...
}
ü§π‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è Java Code (Custom Unchecked Exception):Java// Custom Unchecked Exception (Extends RuntimeException)
class InvalidInputException extends RuntimeException {
    public InvalidInputException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}

public class CustomExceptionDemo {
    public static int calculateSquareRoot(int number) {
        if (number < 0) {
            // Throwing our custom unchecked exception
            throw new InvalidInputException("Cannot calculate square root of a negative number: " + number);
        }
        return (int) Math.sqrt(number);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            System.out.println(calculateSquareRoot(25)); // Output: 5
            System.out.println(calculateSquareRoot(-10)); 
            
        } catch (InvalidInputException e) {
            // We can catch it, even though it's unchecked
            System.err.println("Error: " + e.getMessage()); 
        }
    }
}
üßæ Notebook Points:Javaüìò Custom Exceptions:
‚Üí User-defined exceptions for specific business logic errors

üî¢ Types:
1. Checked: Extend Exception (Must be handled)
2. Unchecked: Extend RuntimeException (Optional handling)
